## purpose
Defines the canonical architectural role of social in CivilizationOS.

## design_intent
Social is the bounded interaction structure
through which actors meet,
relate,
gather,
signal,
influence,
and participate
in non-isolated society.

Social is broader than communication.
Communication is one expression channel;
social is the wider relation and interaction space.

## architectural_position
Social sits between:
- actor identity and life continuity
- family/relationship structures
- organization/community participation
- culture and language expression
- public/private interaction boundary

## required_behavior
- social identity/context must remain explicit
- actor participation basis must remain explicit
- public/private scope must remain explicit
- current and historical social states must remain distinguishable
- social presence must not imply unrestricted access or authority

## canonical_rules
- social visibility must not overwrite relationship truth
- public participation does not imply private entitlement
- historical social trace must remain queryable
- ambiguous social scope fails closed

## state_model
The social domain distinguishes:
- proposed social context
- active social context
- restricted social context
- private social context
- historical social context
- closed social context

## actor_boundary
- participant
- host/operator
- reviewer
- adapter

## decision_matrix
- if social context is unclear, stop interaction-sensitive paths
- if participation basis is unclear, fail closed
- if private/public scope is unclear, route to review
- if social context becomes historical, preserve trace

## review_checklist
- social context is explicit
- participation basis is explicit
- private/public boundary is explicit
- historical distinction is explicit
